# Dev Container environment variables template.

# Docker outside of Docker — workspace `group_add` supplemental GID.
DOCKER_GROUP_ID=102

# Version variables (Node / Playwright / Atlas / Postgres image tags, etc.)
# When you want to change the versions used by this project, copy this file to `.env`,
# set the new values, then build and verify behavior before updating docker-compose.yml.
# If there is no problem, update the `${VAR:-default}` values in docker-compose.yml
# to match the new versions and commit. Otherwise, environments will diverge.
# WORKSPACE_IMAGE_TAG=24.14-bookworm-slim
# PLAYWRIGHT_VERSION=1.57.0
# ATLAS_VERSION=v1.2.0
# GITLEAKS_VERSION=v8.30.1
# POSTGRES_IMAGE_TAG=18

# Non-version variables (Postgres user, password, database name, etc.)
# Override locally via `.env`. To change shared defaults, edit `${VAR:-default}` in docker-compose.yml.
# POSTGRES_USER=postgres
# POSTGRES_PASSWORD=postgres
# POSTGRES_DB=myapp
# POSTGRES_PORT=5432
# API_PORT=8787
# ATLAS_DEV_DB=dev

# --- Docker outside of Docker: app stack (repository root) ---
# After the Dev Container is up, `db` is already running. From the repository root
# (e.g. `/workspace` in the container), build and start only `web` and `api`:
#
#   docker compose up -d
#
# Use the same Compose project name as `.devcontainer/docker-compose.yml` (`name:`),
# so `web`/`api` join the existing project network and can reach the `db` service.
# For a host-only flow (no Dev Container), you need Postgres running separately and
# must align `DATABASE_URL` / credentials with the root `docker-compose.yml`.
